What is an Operating System?
An Operating System(OS) is Software that acts as an interface between 
the user and the computer hardware

without an OS:
-> Application cannot run
-> hardware cannnot be managed efficiently
-> Users cannot interact with the computer in a practical way

Examples:
Linux
windows
macOS

What is Linux?
A Linux is an Open-source Unix-Like Operaing System built around the Linux kernal

Important Point:
Linux itself is  technically the kernal. what most people call "Linux" is a complete operating 
system built from the Linux kernal plus many other tools .

What is Open source?
Open source means the source code is publicly available.
Anyone can:
Read it, write it, improve it, Distribute it accordiing to its License

Linux Architecture
                USER
                  │
                  ▼
        Applications (Chrome, Jenkins, Docker)
                  │
                  ▼
               Shell (Bash, Zsh)
                  │
                  ▼
            Linux Kernel
                  │
      ┌───────────┼───────────┐
      │           │           │
      ▼           ▼           ▼
    CPU        Memory       Disk

Components of Linux
1. kernal
The kernal is core of the operating System.
Responsibilities:
-> Process Management
-> Memory Management
-> Device drivers
-> File System Mangement
-> Networking
-> Security

2. Shell
The shell is the command iterpreter
examples
-> bash
-> zsh
-> fish
-> Ksh

When is type:
ls
the shell:
- read the command
- Find the excutable
- request the kernal to run it
- Display the output

What Happens When You Run ls?
The flow is:
    Keyboard
        │
        ▼
    Bash Shell
        │
        ▼
    Kernel
        │
        ▼
    Filesystem
        │
        ▼
    Kernel returns directory entries
        │
        ▼
    Shell prints the result


User Space Vs kernal Space

User Space

Application run here

Example:
- chrome
- Docker CLI
- vim
- Python
Applications cannot directly access hardware

Kernal Space:
The kernal runs here.
Only the kernel can directly
- Access memory
- Read disks
- Control the CPU
- Manage devices
- Schedule processes

Commands:
uname -> Display the kernal
uname -r -> Display the kernal version
uname -a -> Display the full information
hostname -> Disply the hostname
whoami -> show the current user
id --> Show your user ID (UID), group ID (GID), and group memberships.
pwd -> prit the present working dir
date -> display the current date and time
uptime -> Show how long the system has been running and the current load

Why is Linux preferred for servers and DevOps?
Linux is the preferred operating system for servers and DevOps because it is stable, secure, high-performing, highly customizable, and open source. It also forms the foundation of most modern cloud and container platforms.

